{"title_page": "Kenny Smith", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|American basketball player and sports commentator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name         = Kenny Smith\n| image        = Kenny Smith crop.jpg\n| caption      = Smith in 2015\n| position     = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 3\n| weight_lb    = 170\n| number       = 30, 31\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1965|03|08}}\n| birth_place  = [[Queens, New York]]\n| nationality  = American\n| high_school  = [[Archbishop Molloy]]<br />(Queens, New York)\n| college      = [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]] (1983\u20131987)\n| draft_year   = 1987\n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 6\n| draft_team   = [[Sacramento Kings]]\n| career_start = 1987\n| career_end   = 1997\n| years1       = {{nbay|1987|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1989|end}}\n| team1        = [[Sacramento Kings]]\n| years2       = {{nbay|1989|end}}\n| team2        = [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n| years3       = {{nbay|1990|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1995|end}}\n| team3        = [[Houston Rockets]]\n| years4       = {{nbay|1996|start}}\n| team4        = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years5       = {{nbay|1996|full=y}}\n| team5        = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| years6       = {{nbay|1996|end}}\n| team6        = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| highlights   =\n* 2\u00d7 [[NBA champion]] ([[1994 NBA Finals|1994]], [[1995 NBA Finals|1995]])\n* [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ([[1987\u201388 NBA season|1988]])\n* Consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[1987 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1987]])\n* First-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (1987)\n* 2\u00d7 Second-team All-ACC (1985, 1986)\n* Second-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1983)\n* [[McDonald's All-American]] (1983)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label    = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value    = 9,397 (12.8 ppg)\n| stat2label    = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value    = 1,454 (2.0 rpg)\n| stat3label    = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value    = 4,073 (5.5 apg)\n| bbr           = smithke01\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 Spain]] | [[USA national basketball team|National team]]}}\n}}\n'''Kenneth''' \"'''The Jet'''\" '''Smith''' (born March 8, 1965) is an American [[sports commentator]] and former professional [[basketball]] player in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played in the NBA from 1987 to 1997 as a member of the [[Sacramento Kings]], [[Atlanta Hawks]], [[Houston Rockets]], [[Detroit Pistons]], [[Orlando Magic]], and [[Denver Nuggets]].<ref name=mcdonald/> He won two [[NBA championships]] with Houston.\n\nSmith played [[college basketball]] with the [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina Tar Heels]], earning consensus first-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] honors as a senior in 1987. He was selected by Sacramento in the first round of the [[1987 NBA draft]] with the sixth overall pick, and was named to the [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] with the Kings. After retiring from playing, Smith became a basketball commentator for the [[Emmy]] Award winning ''[[Inside the NBA]]'' on [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]]. He also works as an [[sports analyst|analyst]] for [[CBS]]/[[Turner Broadcasting System|Turner]] during the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament]].<ref name=hoops>[http://www.molloyhs.org/alumni/famous_stanners.cfm \"Famous Stanners: Kenny Smith, Class of 1983\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505010051/http://www.molloyhs.org/alumni/famous_stanners.cfm |date=May 5, 2016 }}. ''www.molloyhs.org''. Retrieved June 16, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSmith was born in [[Queens, New York City]] and grew up in [[LeFrak City]]. He played some of his earliest basketball at New York's [[Riverside Church]]. Smith attended [[Archbishop Molloy High School]], where he was coached by [[Jack Curran]], the winningest high school coach in New York City and New York State history.<ref name=curran>Weber, Bruce. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/15/sports/jack-curran-a-mentor-in-two-sports-dies-at-82.html?_r=0 \"Jack Curran, a Mentor in Two Sports, Dies at 82\"]. [[New York Times]], March 14, 2013. Retrieved June 16, 2016.</ref> Smith was named a [[McDonald's All-American]] in 1983, then played basketball at the [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|University of North Carolina]] for [[Dean Smith]].<ref name=mcdonald/><ref>[http://www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com/content/dam/allamerican/pdfs/Player-Alumni-List-12-2013.pdf \"Boys Alumni: Kenny Smith (1983)\"]. ''www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com''. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref> Smith credits former [[South Carolina State Bulldogs basketball|South Carolina State]] star [[Bobby Lewis (basketball, born 1946)|Bobby Lewis]] with his development as a shooter and ballhandler. Lewis averaged 30.9 points per game and was a First Team Division II All-American as a senior at South Carolina State. He later developed the ''Bobby Lewis Basketball Skills Development Program'', a training regimen that he presented at basketball camps around the country. Smith attended several of his lectures while in high school, and continued to use Lewis's drills throughout his basketball career, and teaches them at his own basketball camps. Of Lewis, Smith said, \"He's the best lecturer ever. He had the best influence in terms of my workout regimen without question.\"<ref name=bartram>Hunt, Donald. [http://www.phillytrib.com/sports/kenny-smith-recognizes-former-bartram-high-star-bobby-lewis/article_1c5a2264-65db-5794-a1e5-53575fb5e77a.html \"Kenny Smith recognizes former Bartram High star Bobby Lewis\"]. ''The Philadelphia Tribune'', April 1, 2016. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\nKenny Smith joined [[Michael Jordan]] as a freshman on a [[1983\u201384 North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball team|North Carolina]] team that was a Pre-season #1 and finished the season ranked #1 with a 28\u20133 record. Smith averaged 9.1 points and 5.0 assists per game, and the Tar Heels lost to [[Indiana Hoosiers|Indiana University]] in the Regional Semifinals of the [[1984 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1984 NCAA Tournament]].<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/players/kenny-smith-1.html \"College Basketball: Kenny Smith\"]. ''www.sports-reference.com''. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref><ref name=fresh>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/north-carolina/1984.html \"1983-84 UNC Tar Heels Roster and Stats\"]. ''www.sports-reference.com''. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref> He led North Carolina to the [[Elite Eight]] in [[1985 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1985]], losing to eventual National Champion [[Villanova Wildcats]]. Smith was named a [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|Consensus All-American]] (1st Team) as senior in [[1987 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|1987]], averaging 16.9 points, 6.1 assists per game while helping North Carolina to return to the Elite Eight. Playing in a game that featured eleven future NBA players, Smith led the Tar Heels with 25 points and 7 assists but they lost to [[Syracuse Orangemen|Syracuse University]], 79\u201375.<ref name=elite>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/boxscores/1987-03-21-north-carolina.html \"Syracuse vs North Carolina, March 21, 1987\"]. ''www.sports-reference.com''. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref><ref name=time/>\n\nDuring his career at North Carolina, Smith averaged 12.9 points and 6.0 assists per game, while shooting .512 from the field, and .823 from the [[free throw]] line. In 1986\u201387, the first season the NCAA added [[three-point field goal]]s, Smith shot .408.<ref name=ncaa/> As of 2016, he ranks second in school history in total assists (768), fourth in total steals (195), and fifth in assists per game.<ref name=time>[http://www.goheels.com/fls/3350/pdf/MBB2016/UNCRecordBook2016.pdf?SPID=12965 \"Carolina Basketball: 2015-16 Fact & Records Book\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810072915/http://www.goheels.com/fls/3350/pdf/MBB2016/UNCRecordBook2016.pdf?SPID=12965 |date=August 10, 2016 }}. ''www.goheels.com''. 37-52. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref> Smith helped North Carolina to a record of 115\u201322 from the 1983\u201384 to 1986\u201387 seasons, including two Elite Eight appearances (1985 and 1987) and a [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Sweet Sixteen]] appearance in 1986. They won the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) regular season conference championships in 1984 and 1987, and tied for first in 1985. North Carolina never finished lower than 8th in the [[2015\u201316 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings|national polls]] during Smith's four years at the school.<ref name=time/>\n\n===International career===\nSmith represented the United States in the [[1986 FIBA World Championship]], on a team that included [[David Robinson (basketball)|David Robinson]], [[Muggsy Bogues]] and [[Steve Kerr]]. He was second on the team in scoring behind [[Charles Smith (basketball, born 1965)|Charles Smith]] with 14.7 points per game. Smith scored 23 points to lead the US to an 87\u201385 win and the Gold Medal over a [[Soviet Union national basketball team|Soviet Union]] team that featured [[Arvydas Sabonis]].<ref name=fiba>Jackson, Tim W. [https://books.google.com/books?id=QRcaAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59&dq=kenny+smith+fiba&source=bl&ots=xgha9cwKEN&sig=xMUV04hrrz47umbJ2yVc1njcK4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj2xZa22rTNAhUBymMKHRfFBGY4ChDoAQgsMAM#v=onepage&q=kenny%20smith%20fiba&f=false ''Gone Pro: North Carolina: Tar Heel Stars Who Became Pros'']. Covington, Kentucky: Clerisy, 2014. {{ISBN|1578605458}}. Google Books. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref><ref name=gold>[http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/game/p/gid/A/grid/12/rid/873/sid/2911/tid/379/_/1986_World_Championship_for_Men/statistic.html \"1986 World Championship for Men. July 20, 1986\"]. ''www.fiba.com''. Retrieved June 19, 2016.</ref>\n\n==NBA playing career==\n\n===Early career===\nSmith was selected as a 6'3\" 170 lb point guard by the [[Sacramento Kings]] with the sixth pick of the [[1987 NBA draft]]. He was named to the [[NBA All-Rookie Team]] (1st Team) after averaging 13.8 points and 7.1 assists per game for the Kings.  Smith began his NBA career playing for [[NBA Hall of Fame|Hall of Famer]] [[Bill Russell]], who was head coach for Kings until he was fired 58 games into the '87-88 season.<ref>Poindexter, Bill. [http://articles.latimes.com/1989-12-24/sports/sp-2092_1_bill-russell \"Sacramento Fans Have No Problem With Dumping Bill Russell\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', December 24, 1989. Retrieved June 22, 2016.</ref> Smith was traded to the Atlanta Hawks midway through the [[1989\u201390 NBA season|1989\u201390 season]], where he was a [[Substitution (sport)|reserve player]] for the first time in his career, averaging 7.7 points per game while only starting five of thirty-games he played for the Hawks.<ref name=mcdonald/>\n\n===Houston Rockets===\nAfter the 1989\u201390 season, Smith was traded to the [[Houston Rockets]], where he would spend the next six seasons. In [[1990\u201391 NBA season|1990\u201391]] Smith averaged 17.7 points per game while leading the Rockets in assists per game (7.1) and free throw percentage (.844).<ref name=led>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/1991.html \"1990-91 Houston Rockets Roster and Stats\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved June 24, 2016.</ref> He helped the Rockets to a 52\u201330 record, the best regular season in franchise history at the time. They were swept by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] in the first round of the playoffs.<ref name=rec>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/ \"Houston Rockets Franchise Index\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved June 24, 2016.</ref> Smith finished 17th in voting for the [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award]], just ahead of teammate [[Hakeem Olajuwon]].<ref name=finish>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/awards/awards_1991.html#mvp \"1990-91 Awards Voting\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved June 25, 2016.</ref>\n\nHead Coach [[Don Chaney]] was fired after posting a record of only 26\u201326 in the [[1991\u201392 NBA season|1991\u201392 season]]. He was replaced by former Rocket player [[Rudy Tomjanovich]], who went 16\u201314 to close out the season, missing the playoffs by one game. The Rockets then went 55\u201327 in [[1992\u201393 NBA season|1992\u201393]], losing to [[Seattle SuperSonics]] in the second round of the playoffs in seven games. Smith helped to force a game seven against Seattle by scoring 30 points, shooting 4\u20136 from three-point range, in a Game 6 victory for Houston.<ref name=battle>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199305200HOU.html \"Seattle SuperSonics at Houston Rockets Box Score, May 20, 1993\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved June 29, 2016.</ref><ref name=jump>[http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-21/sports/sp-37763_1_kenny-smith \"Smith Lifts Rockets Into Game 7 : NBA playoffs: Guard scores 30 points as Houston pulls away from Seattle in third quarter for a 103-90 victory\"]. ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', May 21, 1993. Retrieved June 29, 2016.</ref> The Rockets won back-to-back championships in [[1993\u201394 NBA season|1993\u201394]] and [[1994\u201395 NBA season|1994\u201395]]. From the 1992\u201393 to 1994\u201395 seasons, Kenny Smith averaged 11.7 points and 4.5 assists per game, with a three-point percentage of .425. In 57 playoff games during the same period, Smith had nearly identical averages of 11.6 points and 4.3 assists, shooting .456 from three-point range.<ref name=mcdonald/> In the first game of the 1995 Finals against the [[Orlando Magic]], Smith had 23 points, 9 assists and made seven [[three-pointer]]s, including the game-tying shot which sent the game into [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]]. Kenny Smith's 7 three pointers in the first game of the 1995 NBA Finals was an NBA record at the time. The Rockets won the game 120\u2013118, and went on to sweep the Magic in four games.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/encyclopedia/moments/60moments_hm_21-31.html \"The 60 Greatest Playoff Moments: Honorable Mention\"]. ''www.nba.com''. Retrieved on January 28, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199506070ORL.html \"Houston Rockets at Orlando Magic Box Score, June 7, 1995\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved June 26, 2016.</ref>\n\nSmith had been gradually losing playing time to [[Sam Cassell]],<ref name=sam>Howard, Johnette. [https://www.si.com/vault/1995/11/13/8098745/sam-i-am-with-teammates-foes-and-refs-houston-rocket-point-guard-sam-cassell-likes-to-talk-the-talk-and-hes-happy-to-back-it-up-come-crunch-time \"SAM I AM WITH TEAMMATES, FOES AND REFS, HOUSTON ROCKET POINT GUARD SAM CASSELL LIKES TO TALK THE TALK-- AND HE'S HAPPY TO BACK IT UP COME CRUNCH TIME]. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', November 13, 1995. [[SI Vault]]. Retrieved June 28, 0216.</ref> but he continued to be the Rockets' starting point guard through the [[1995\u201396 NBA season|1995\u201396 season]]. Although Smith's points, assists, steals and minutes per game declined for the fifth straight season, he was still productive in 1995\u201396. He averaged 8.5 points and 3.6 assists per game, and shot .382 from three-point range and .821 from the free throw line.<ref name=mcdonald/> The Rockets finished fifth in the NBA Western Conference with a 48\u201334 record, upsetting the fourth-seeded [[1995\u201396 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]] in the first round before being swept in the second round by eventual Finals runner-up [[1995\u201396 Seattle SuperSonics season|Seattle SuperSonics]].<ref name=broom>McGuire, Paul. [http://www.red94.net/14511/14511/# \"History in Hindsight: The Houston Rockets, The Seattle SuperSonics, and Hakeem Olajuwon\u2019s greatest foe\"]. ''www.red94.net'', July 28, 2014. Retrieved June 28, 2016.</ref> In game four of the series against the Lakers, Smith had 17 points, 6 assists and was 4\u20134 from three-point range to help the Rockets win the series clincher 102\u201394. The win against the Lakers also marked the final NBA game for [[Magic Johnson]], who returned to the NBA that season after a five-year absence.<ref name=clinch>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199605020HOU.html \"Los Angeles Lakers at Houston Rockets Box Score, May 2, 1996\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved June 30, 2016.</ref><ref name=laker>Hansford, Corey. [http://www.lakersnation.com/throwback-thursday-magic-johnson-makes-a-comeback-in-1996/2013/12/12/ \"Throwback Thursday: Magic Johnson Makes A Comeback In 1996\"]. ''www.lakersnation.com'', December 12, 2013. Retrieved June 30, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Final year===\nThe Rockets released Smith after the 1995\u201396 season, and he signed with the [[1996\u201397 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]]. He played only nine games with the Pistons before he was waived and signed by the [[1996\u201397 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]], who released Smith after only six games. Smith then signed with the [[1996\u201397 Denver Nuggets season|Denver Nuggets]], where he would finish his career as a player.<ref name=mcdonald/> Smith played sparingly for the playoff-bound Pistons and the Magic, but got the last meaningful playing time of his career with the Nuggets, a team that won only 21 games that season. Smith averaged 7.9 points and 3.1 assists while playing just under twenty minutes per game. Overall, Smith averaged 6.3 points and 2.4 assists per game, the lowest averages of his career, while his three-point percentage of .437 (59/135) was the second highest of his career, and the fourth season in which he shot better than 40 percent on three-pointers.<ref name=mcdonald/>\n\nIn his professional career, Smith scored 9,397 points (12.8 avg.), recorded 4,073 assists (5.5 avg) while shooting .480 from the field, .399 from three-point range, and .829 from the free throw line.<ref name=mcdonald/> He finished in the NBA top ten in three-point percentage three times (1992\u201393, 1993\u201394, 1994\u201395), and top ten in free throw percentage twice (1992\u201393 and 1993\u201394). In the [[1988\u201389 Sacramento Kings season|1988\u201389 season]] Smith was fifth in the league in minutes played, seventh in minutes per game, and tenth in total assists. Smith's career three-point percentage of .399 still ranks 42nd in NBA history.<ref name=mcdonald>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/s/smithke01.html \"Kenny Smith\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved on January 28, 2010.</ref> Smith holds the Denver Nuggets franchise record for career three-point percentage (.425), and he continues to rank among the all-time leaders in several categories for the Sacramento Kings and the Houston Rockets.<ref name=bestnugget>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/DEN/leaders_career.html \"Denver Nuggets Career Leaders\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved July 1, 2016.</ref><ref name=top>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/SAC/leaders_career.html \"Sacramento Kings Career Leaders\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved July 1, 2016.</ref><ref name=jets>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/leaders_season.html \"Houston Rockets Season Leaders\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved July 1, 2016.</ref><ref name=freebie>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/teams/HOU/leaders_career.html \"Houston Rockets Career Leaders\"]. ''www.basketball-reference.com''. Retrieved July 1, 2016.</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player s