ar on Terror}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraeus, David}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Frisian descent]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Commandants of the United States Army Command and General Staff College]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]]\n[[Category:Commandeurs of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Counter-insurgency theorists]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:School of Foreign Service alumni]]\n[[Category:Honorary Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of Orange-Nassau]]\n[[Category:Military leaders of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Order of National Security Merit members]]\n[[Category:People from Cornwall, New York]]\n[[Category:Petraeus scandal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Cross of Merit of the Minister of Defence of the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Defense Superior Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Meritorious Service Decoration]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NATO Meritorious Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Polish Army Medal]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Woodrow Wilson School of Public and International Affairs alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Sboylan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpeeches, public remarks, interviews, and op-eds", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Petraeus"}
{"title_page": "Submerged continent", "text_new": "{{Short description|Continental mass, extensive in size, but mainly undersea}}\n\n{{More references|date=August 2015}}\n\n[[File:Kerguelen-Plateau-Topography.jpg|thumbnail|Kerguelen Plateau Topography]]\n\nA '''submerged continent''' or '''sunken continent''' is a [[continent|continental mass]], extensive in size, but mainly [[underwater|undersea]]. The terminology is used by some [[paleogeologist]]s and [[geographer]]s in reference to some land masses. \n\nThe main examples in this class are the [[Kerguelen Plateau]], [[Seychelles microcontinent]], [[Mauritia (microcontinent)|Mauritia]], and [[Zealandia]].\n\nSubmerged continents have been sought and speculated about in regard to a possible \"[[list of lost lands|lost continent]]\" underwater in the [[Atlantic Ocean]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1966/08/21/archives/atlantis-search-shifts-to-aegean-lost-continent-legend-held-based.html ATLANTIS SEARCH SHIFTS TO AEGEAN; Lost Continent Legend Held Based on False Statistics] 1966 New York Times</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 4, 1882 |title=A Submerged Continent |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/378295667/ |work=Los Angeles Times |quote=Ignatius Donnelly has recently published a work in defence of the story that a continent known among the ancients as Atlantis was sunk in the Atlantic Ocean by an earthquake. |accessdate=2019-05-28}}</ref> There was also a search in the 1930s for [[Lemuria (continent)|Lemuria]], believed to have possibly been a submerged continent between the Indian and African coasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=x5cQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3JEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4796,4542041&dq=submerged+continent|title=Submerged continent| date=November 28, 1932 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{annotated link|Continental fragment}}\n* {{annotated link|List of mythological places}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Continents of the world}}\n{{Submerged landmasses}}\n\n{{Topography-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Continental fragments]]\n[[Category:Continents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Continental mass, extensive in size, but mainly undersea}}\n{{More references|date=August 2015}}\n\n[[File:Kerguelen-Plateau-Topography.jpg|thumbnail|Kerguelen Plateau Topography]]\n\nA '''submerged continent''' or '''sunken continent''' is a [[continent|continental mass]], extensive in size, but mainly [[underwater|undersea]]. The terminology is used by some [[paleogeologist]]s and [[geographer]]s in reference to some land masses. \n\nThe main examples in this class are the [[Kerguelen Plateau]], [[Seychelles microcontinent]], [[Mauritia (microcontinent)|Mauritia]], and [[Zealandia]].\n\n\nSubmerged continents have been sought and speculated about in regard to a possible \"[[Lost lands|lost continent]]\" underwater in the [[Atlantic Ocean]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1966/08/21/archives/atlantis-search-shifts-to-aegean-lost-continent-legend-held-based.html ATLANTIS SEARCH SHIFTS TO AEGEAN; Lost Continent Legend Held Based on False Statistics] 1966 New York Times</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=April 4, 1882 |title=A Submerged Continent |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/378295667/ |work=Los Angeles Times |quote=Ignatius Donnelly has recently published a work in defence of the story that a continent known among the ancients as Atlantis was sunk in the Atlantic Ocean by an earthquake. |accessdate=2019-05-28}}</ref> There was also a search in the 1930s for [[Lemuria (continent)|Lemuria]], believed to have possibly been a submerged continent between the Indian and African coasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=x5cQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3JEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4796,4542041&dq=submerged+continent|title=Submerged continent| date=November 28, 1932 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{annotated link|Continental fragment}}\